56":"1556","1483":"1483","1460":"1460","about 1460":"about 1460","1549":"1549","about 1483":"about 1483","Byfield, Northamptonshire, England":"Byfield, Northamptonshire, England","<England>":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Leeson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Northamptonshire): metronymic from   Leece  1."],"variants":[{"name":"Leece","meanings":["English: from a medieval female personal name, <i>Lece</i>, a short form of <i>Lettice</i> (from Latin <i>Laetitia</i>, meaning ‘happiness, gaiety’).","English: variant of   Lees  .","Irish: shortened form of Gaelic <i>Mac Giolla Íosa</i>, Manx <i>Mac Guilley Yeesey</i> ‘son of <i>Giolla Íosa</i> (devotee or servant of Jesus)’. Ballaleece (‘Leece's farm’) in Kirk German was the family's main seat."]},{"name":"Layson","meanings":["English (Kent): possibly a variant of   Leeson  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":89,"year":"1549","juli